comment_text:
Pls read before selecting books as a  beginner :

Scratch this, if you want to get into reading try with small adventure books with a good storyline so you don't get bored and stop reading after a while and start feeling miserable... Later you can slowly explore different genres and authors...I would never recommend you to straight away start non-fiction until you find your preferred genre in books that you can truly enjoy. 

Trust me I started my reading journey with books as simple as Thea Stilton series, Enid Blyton , and Nancy Drew , and now have transformed into a voracious reader of books like A thousand splendid suns, the girl who knew too much , A litte life,kite runner, girl in pieces , Tuesdays with Morrie ,or the colour of water by James McBride, All having equally different and engaging stories. 
 
Thanks for Reading, I hope you find good books to read â¤

MY NEW BOOK HERES A PREVIEW GUYSSS!

     â€œI canâ€™t breathe!â€ she said dying of laughter in my arms.  We were just two teens laughing over a stupid video we pulled off of the internet, of an AI cat dancing to a song on top of a cup of hot chocolate.  I know, it seems stupid, but she thought it was funny.  Her laugh made me laugh.  We were . . . laughing . . . living.
Actually, let me introduce who â€œweâ€ are.
Iâ€™m your average teenage boy.  Hoodie, pajama pants, brown straight hair, emerald green eyes and about 5 foot 10.  My name was Levi.  The average name for the most average American boy.  I was in my junior year at Redwood high school, a crappy school that FORCED you to write random junk on a piece of paper, that would eventually be thrown away.  I obviously wasnâ€™t a straight A student.  I mean in elementary years I was, but as soon as I reached my independence in middle school,  I lost everything.  Ability to focus in class, my empathy towards others.  I wasnâ€™t ever really nice to anyone in middle school, or freshman and sophomore year.  But last month that changed.
I met her.
The girl of my dreams.
The one I could make laugh by dropping my pencil in class, or showing her stupid, pointless videos off the internet.  Once I met her, everything sorta came back to me.  I started changing.  I acted kinder towards others, started picking up my grades.  Focused.  Something about her just changed me.  I donâ€™t know if it was her scent.  The scent of flowers, or the way she dressed, always in her jean shorts and short top.  Or if it was her blonde hair, or even her bright blue eyes.  Maybe it was her laugh, of the way she helped me study after school.  The way she made me flashcards, the way she gave me the homework answers.  I donâ€™t know what it was.
Because, it wasnâ€™t one thing.
It was everything about her I liked.  
We were at my house, scrolling through a plethora of videos.  Laughing at all them.  Even if they made no sense.  One said . . .
â€œHow do I clean my toilet with a cheeseburger?â€ 
Yeah, something that I would have laughed at in kindergarten.  Something I didnâ€™t laugh at.  But her laugh made me laugh.  The way she lied on my chest as I scrolled through videos, holding my arm out in front of her face so she could see.
Life mattered now.
My parents were always harassing me to get a â€œgirlfriendâ€ and I was never interested.  I didnâ€™t feel like putting all my trust into a random person I didnâ€™t even know.  I knew I could easily fumble, or I would get used by that special person.
But when I saw her in the hallway on my way to English third period, I knew I had to try.  My friends even annoyed me about girls.  They all liked someone, and started making matches for me with random girls, to try to help.
Help.
I tried to ignore it, but I also worried about it.  I never went to a school dance with a girl unlike them.  I never went out to lunch, or studied with someone the opposite sex of me.  I was just worried.  I didnâ€™t want to be alone.
I lived in a small town called â€œRedwood Townâ€.  It was very basic.  Home to Barry Redwood.  Iâ€™ll explain some of this towns history.
Barry Redwood lived from 1823-1860.  His history started off as a young boy, around the age of twelve.  His mother had died when he was five years old, due to an alcohol addiction.  He grew up depressed, with his strict dad.  His dad would make him walk around town in 95 degree weather, going door to door selling newspapers for his new publishing business.  Since his dad was busy with work, and made him work also, he grew up alone and imprisoned under his fatherâ€™s wrath.  He had no freedom.  When he was alone though, he would practice his math problems.  He would sit at his desk every time he was free and alone and practice his math problems.  Math cured his mind.  He was the top mathematician at school, and was dedicated to that role.
His dad was not supportive of it at all.
â€œITS A WASTE OF TIME WRITING NUMBERS ON PAPER!â€
â€œTHIS WILL NOT FLY IN THIS HOUSE!â€
â€œYOU ARE GOING TO WORK FOR MY BUSINESS!â€
Barry ignored his father.  
At least I donâ€™t need to type fake news stories on my typewriter seven hours a day, trying to start drama in town.  Maybe cause a riot.  Maybe bring everyone apart.  Whatever my stupid bean-sized mind had in plan. Barry would think to himself.  
One day, he decided to run away.  
No one really knows what happened to him.  Some say he took his life, or got lost trying to find â€œthe perfect lifeâ€, but other theories say he did find â€œthe perfect lifeâ€, and lived inside a tiny house on the beach, by the glistening, sparkling ocean.
I was sorta like Barry before I met her.  Anna.  The girl of my dreams.  And now look where we were.  I was doing better at life, and she was happy.

comment_text:
I started getting annoyed with these books the minute my husband (middle school English teacher) came home and told me one of his young female students was reading Icebreaker in his class. Her mom didn't care. And the student in question had new smut she was reading in school every other week. Likely out of her mother's collection. Because TikTok and social media are influencing these kids to read these books. His school has already had problems that arose from these books that became so severe kids aren't allowed to bring their own books to school and if they want to read it has to be something they check out of the school library. Students have been caught literally acting out scenes in the books in the school. Or abusing their friend or bf/gf because they want to be more like characters in the books they are reading. My husband is literally thinking about quitting his job because he can't stand it anymore. These incidents are just the tip of the iceberg especially with TikTok. The challenge are getting out of hand too with these kids. They just had to suspend another kid yesterday because of the "knockout challenge".

They need to stop putting these books in these covers that make them also look like they should be in the YA or Middle Grade section. They need to stop pushing them on children. They need to stop romanticizing abuse and SA. It needs to be shelved appropriately. Children shouldn't even be allowed to buy them when they card for explicit video games and movies and even music. I don't care what adults read as long as they aren't acting like idiots and treating the content like it's a positive.

Reading comprehension and media literacy is in the toilet and we need to start protecting kids from this garbage.

These stupid and lazy cartoony covers are making things worse. There's a reason covers for different books used to looks a certain way. You could usually tell just by looking what kind of book it is and who it was geared towards. You can't anymore. And kids are suffering because of it.

video_title: 5 Books Every Book Bro Needs To Read!
comment_text:
I would go with the following in no particular order...

Red Rising
*And I agree the first book is thoroughly mediocre but damn does the series take off in amazing ways in Golden Son et al.

Butcher's Crossing

I never imagined a western could be done without cowboys and native americans but William's pulls it off spectacularly and with some of the most evocative nature descriptions you will ever read.

The Hobbit

It is basically the perfect book as far as I am concerned even if it is one of the most known works in the english language.

Starship Troopers

Heinlein is perhaps the best SciFi author of two generations and the novel will cause you to ponder your thoughts on a person's role and obligations within society. Given how much we focus (in America at least) on what our rights are and what we are entitled too I think it is worth to ask.....what do I owe to society? And this book will demand that from you.

The Promise by Ann Weisgarber

This is my kind of love story. It's gritty, it's messy and it comes with more unideal strings attached than you might like. A well to do Catherine Wainwright is forced by circumstance to accept a marriage proposal from a former suitor. She leaves the uppercrust of early 1900s Dayton, OH and makes her way to Galveston where he new husband owns a reasonably successful dairy farm. It is set against the backdrop of one of the most devastating storms to ever hit the gulf coast.

Iâ€™m 20, from a lower middle-class family. Mere aas paas ke log ek normal life chahte hain â€“ govt job, shaadi, settle. But mera mindset alag hai. Mujhe casual life nahi jeeni. Mera dream hai ki main ek extraordinary life jeeyu â€“ jahan fame aur money dono ho.

Mere paas knowledge bhi hai aur passion bhi, par sach batau to ek bada darr bhi hai â€“ ki kahin main padhai aur skills dono me mehnat karu, par aakhir me jo chahta hoon wo achieve hi na kar pau.

Abhi confuse hoon â€“ kya main safe route choose karu (sirf government job ki preparation) ya risk lekar apna passion follow karu (content creation, skills build karna)? Dar yeh hai ki kahi study ko ignore karke future spoil na kar du, aur risk lekar regret na karu.
